# Keep the image-pipeline whitepaper in sync

`docs/image_pipeline_whitepaper.md` is the canonical study guide for the
detection → filter → align → embed → cluster → match pipeline. It includes
sequence diagrams, flowcharts, model contracts, algorithm pseudocode, and a
configuration cheat-sheet.

When you change any file matched by this rule, **before ending the turn**,
ask yourself: does my change invalidate any claim in the whitepaper?

## Triggers — update the whitepaper when you change

- **Stage flow / order**: e.g. add or remove a stage in `FaceProcessor.process`,
  reorder filters in `FaceFilters.apply`, or alter the Clusterify / Filter
  use-case orchestration.
- **Model contract**: input size, anchor count, regressor stride, embedding
  dim, manifest schema (`ModelManifest`, `models/manifest.json`).
- **Algorithm choice**: switch detector variants, NMS strategy, alignment
  fit (similarity vs perspective), clustering algorithm, distance metric.
- **Configurable knobs**: any new / changed / renamed property in
  `PipelineConfig` — including its default, range, or class
  (MODEL CONTRACT / TUNABLE HEURISTIC / USER SETTING DEFAULT). Update the
  cheat-sheet table in §10.
- **Threading / memory**: dispatcher choice, buffer reuse rules, bitmap
  recycle discipline.
- **Persistence shape**: `ClusterEntity` / `ClusterImageEntity` columns,
  centroid / embedding dim.

## How to update

1. Locate the affected section (the §-numbered ToC / `### N.M` headings
   make this fast).
2. Update the prose, the diagram (Mermaid), AND the cheat-sheet table if
   relevant — the three views must agree.
3. If your change spans multiple sections (e.g. a new stage), also revisit
   §0 (at-a-glance flowchart), §13 (end-to-end sequences), §14 (file
   index), and §15 (one-sentence-per-stage recap).

## When NOT to update

- Pure refactors (renames, log message tweaks, comment-only edits) that
  don't change behaviour, contracts, or thresholds.
- Bug fixes that restore documented behaviour rather than change it.

If unsure, prefer to update — drift is the failure mode this rule exists to
prevent.

## Don't forget the commit

Per `cursor-artifacts.mdc`, the whitepaper is committed alongside source
changes. Fold whitepaper edits into the same work commit (or an immediate
follow-up) so reviewers see the doc move in lockstep with the code.
